Reasoning: The paper deals with stochastic control and team problems, which are typically studied in the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) as it discusses the conditions under which decision makers' observations are conditionally independent. The use of LQG team problems suggests that the paper may also fall under the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper's focus on optimal solutions and regularity conditions suggests that it may also belong to the mathematical aspects (cs.MA) sub-category. Finally, the paper's analysis of dynamic teams suggests that it may also fall under the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
